{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17499736","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17499736"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T10:01:59+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T10:01:59+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1531"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"1531","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/1531"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.05,0.18,0.01,0.63,0.13]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"1531"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"83508"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"1531","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/1531"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1531"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"68381"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"3"},{"type":"tags","id":"19"},{"type":"tags","id":"25"},{"type":"tags","id":"64"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"808"},{"type":"tags","id":"1115"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"5219"},{"type":"contributions","id":"6373"},{"type":"contributions","id":"28464"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"83508","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/83508"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 70-year-old man presents to his general practitioner with a hard lesion that has been growing on his ear for the two past years. He has worked as a farmer for many years and was not one to wear a hat. On examination the lesion appears to be strongly rooted to the skin and can be seen in the following photograph (Image).\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most likely diagnosis?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Pyogenic granuloma","Basal cell carcinoma","Foreign body reaction","Cutaneous horn","Malignant melanoma"],"correctOptions":[3],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ECutaneous Horn\u003C/strong\u003E: This painless skin lesion had been slowly growing for about two years. These cutaneous horns are slow-growing projections above the skin surface. Their aetiology is uncertain, but probably related to solar radiation - as the most common sites for the lesions are the face and hands. Most are harmless and has evolved from benign growths like seborrheic keratosis, but up to 40% may have underlying scc-in-situ. They can be removed surgically.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EMalignant melanoma: \u003C/strong\u003Eless likely with this slow growing appearance of a hard growth. Melanomas are more commonly flat lesions with ragged edges and discolouration.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EBasal cell carcinoma\u003C/strong\u003E (BCC)is an important differential diagnosis to consider in this site, however the lesion in the photograph does not show features of a BCC.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EPyogenic granuloma\u003C/strong\u003E is a rapidly growing fleshy nodule that bleeds easily. The slow growth over two years excludes this diagnosis.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EForeign body reaction \u003C/strong\u003Eis unlikely in this location.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Cutaneous horns are slow growing, often benign growths in sun affected areas","Ruling out malignant skin lesions is important in all skin growths"],"references":["Thiers BH, Strat N, Snyder AN, et al. Cutaneous Horn. [Updated 2022 May 8]. In: StatPearls [Internet]. Treasure Island (FL): StatPearls Publishing; 2022 Jan-. Available from: https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/books/NBK563280/","Thappa DM, Garg BR, Thadeus J, Ratnakar C. Cutaneous horn: a brief review and report of a case. J Dermatol. 1997 Jan;24(1):34-7. doi: 10.1111/j.1346-8138.1997.tb02735.x. PMID: 9046738. Avaialble from: https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/9046738/","Copcu E, Sivrioglu N, Culhaci N. Cutaneous horns: are these lesions as innocent as they seem to be? World J Surg Oncol. 2004 Jun 3;2:18. doi: 10.1186/1477-7819-2-18. PMID: 15176977; PMCID: PMC421749. Available from: https://pmc.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/articles/PMC421749/"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"68381"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1531"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[{"type":"media","id":"15722"}]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"media","id":"15722","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/media/15722"},"attributes":{"mimeType":"image/jpeg","url":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/52442848-f2a0-418a-9a26-0e45a55ad6c4.jpg","thumbUrl":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/52442848-f2a0-418a-9a26-0e45a55ad6c4.jpg","isProcessed":true,"width":497,"height":480}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"68381","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/68381"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-02-04T20:49:12+10:30","updatedAt":"2025-02-04T20:50:08+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"1531"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"83508"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"3","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/3"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\uddf4","name":"Dermatology","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:49:42+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"19","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/19"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udd2a","name":"General Surgery","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updat